<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 8:18<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I27da1d50630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>8.</label.designator><headtext>Relevancy</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71ff01c682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>8:18.</label.designator><headtext>Handwriting evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Scientific evidence to identify handwriting is admissible if the expert witness bases his opinion on recognized scientific techniques concerning spacing, shading, ink, and other characteristics. <eos/><bos/>He may testify about whether a disputed writing and a genuine writing were done by the same individual and about tracing or alterations without comparison.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic47baf707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The lay witness may testify that he knows or recognizes the handwriting,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic47baf717fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] but he cannot state an opinion based on comparison of the writings.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic47baf727fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The expert witness may use crayon drawings, enlarged photographs, magnifying glasses, and other materials to illustrate for the jury the basis of his opinion.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic47baf737fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The jury may also compare the two writings. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-901" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2f07f3407fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-9-901(b)(3)</cite.query> requires that handwriting specimens that the trier of fact or an expert witness will compare shall be furnished to the opposite party no later than 10 days prior to trial.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic47bd6807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>An expert who conducted a forensic accounting may testify that there are significant discrepancies as to checks written from a particular account. <eos/><bos/>In this case, the accountant was trained to look for things that were odd or suspicious, including discrepancies in signatures.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic47bd6817fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Also, handwriting evidence is not required in every case where a written document is offered so long as there is other evidence, circumstantial or otherwise, to make a prima facie showing of authenticity.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic47bd6827fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic47baf707fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-serial-number="1911012416" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I2f0645927fc011ea988285db8533e975">E.B. Martin &amp; Sons v. Bank of Leesburg, 137 Ga. 285, 73 S.E. 387 (1911)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic47baf717fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-901" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2f06bac07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-9-901(b)(2)</cite.query>: <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[T]he following are examples of authentication or identification conforming with the requirements of this Code section: … (2) Nonexpert opinion as to the genuineness of handwriting, based upon familiarity not acquired for purposes of the litigation.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic47baf727fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-serial-number="1892007550" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I2f0708e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Wimbish v. State, 89 Ga. 294, 15 S.E. 325 (1892)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic47baf737fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-serial-number="1955105169" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2f077e127fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hilliard v. State, 92 Ga. App. 294, 88 S.E.2d 425 (1955)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic47bd6807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-9-901" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I2f081a507fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-9-901(b)(3)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic47bd6817fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-serial-number="2048491403" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2f088f817fc011ea988285db8533e975">Carr v. State, 829 S.E.2d 641 (Ga. Ct. App. 2019)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic47bd6827fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017143" w-serial-number="2009116931" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I2f0904b27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Williams v. State, 280 Ga. 584, 630 S.E.2d 370 (2006)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="254"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 8:18<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
